						<p class="first">Graduate students hold a unique position on post-secondary campuses. They take on the roles of students, staff and/or faculty members, and sometimes they can feel like they don’t really have a place where they “fit.”</p>
						<h4 class="spotlight">Graduate students hold a unique position on post-secondary campuses</h4>
						<p>To ensure graduate students feel appreciated and valued, Wilfrid Laurier University, the Faculty of Graduate and Postdoctoral Studies and the Graduate Students’ Association (GSA) have worked diligently to provide non-academic spaces specifically for graduate students on our campuses. Most recently, this was achieved through the GSA’s gift to fund a new Graduate Student Lounge at Laurier Brantford.</p>
						<p>“The GSA felt it was important to provide community space for our Brantford graduate students to relax, network and host events,” says Ellen Menage, executive director of Laurier’s GSA. “It’s a way to foster community and to reiterate the important role graduate students play at Laurier.”</p>
						<p>To bring the lounge to life, the GSA and Laurier Brantford graduate students met in the pre-renovated space in the Odeon basement. There they held discussions and focus groups in order to build a space that suited the needs of Brantford’s graduate students.</p>
						<img src="images/impact/impact3-gsalounge2.jpg" class="right-image wide-image" alt="The New GSA Lounge"/>
						<h4 class="spotlight">“They wanted it to feel loungey,”</h4>
						<p>“They wanted it to feel loungey,” says Ellen. “The space already had a kitchenette and they were happy to have that, but they also wanted comfortable seating, open spaces and lockers for their personal items.”</p>
						<p>With overstuffed chairs, a bank of lockers and tables for more formal events, it seems the GSA has delivered on the students’ desires. Ellen concludes, “It’s multi-functional, and designed by the students for the students. They now have a space for them to engage and connect. They are comfortable being themselves in this space... It’s a space where they belong.”</p>
